|rev7         = ''[[Slant Magazine|Slant]]''
|rev7Score    = {{Rating|4|5}} <small>(2007)</small><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/music_review.asp?ID=1234 | title = U2: The Joshua Tree - Music Review | publisher = ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' | first = Jimmy | last = Newlin | date = 2007-11-18 | accessdate = 2009-12-02}}</ref>
|rev8         = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''
|rev8Score    = {{Rating|5|5}} <small>(2007)</small><ref name="uncut-review">{{cite magazine | url = http://www.uncut.co.uk/music/u2/reviews/10793 | title = U2 - The Joshua Tree Re-Mastered (R1987) - Review | magazine = [[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]] | first = Andrew | last = Mueller | accessdate = 2010-04-20}}</ref>
}}

Album reviews were almost universally positive, and the best of U2's career to that point. ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine said that "For a band that's always specialized in inspirational, larger-than-life gestures <U+2013> a band utterly determined to be Important <U+2013> ''The Joshua Tree'' could be the big one, and that's precisely what it sounds like."<ref name="rs">{{cite magazine | url = http://web.archive.org/web/20080618150201/www.rollingstone.com/artists/u2/albums/album/108063/review/6067670/the_joshua_tree | title = U2: The Joshua Tree: Music Reviews | magazine = [[Rolling Stone]] | first = Steve | last = Pond | date = 1987-04-09 | accessdate = 2010-04-26}}</ref> The review described the album's sound as "wed[ding] the diverse textures of ''The Unforgettable Fire'' to fully formed songs, many of them as aggressive as the hits on ''War''".<ref name="rs" /> Steve Morse of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' echoed these sentiments in his review, stating "It's another spiritual progress report, enwrapped in music that strikes a healthy balance between the lushness of their last album, 1984's ''The Unforgettable Fire'', and the more volcanic rock of their early years." Morse called it "their most challenging work to date" and the "most rewarding rock record of the new year".<ref name="globe">{{cite web | url = http://www.boston.com/ae/music/packages/U2Fleetcenter/album_review_joshua_tree/ | title = U2's 'The Joshua Tree': A spiritual progress report | publisher = ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' | first = Steve | last = Morse | date = 1987-03-08 | accessdate = 2009-12-02}}</ref> ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' gave the album a rating of five-stars, noting that "their reinvention of stadium rock sounds as impassioned as ever" and that the album strikes "a finely balanced mix of intimacy and power".<ref name="q">{{cite web | url = http://www.tower.com/details/details.cfm?wapi=106666300 | title = Music: The Joshua Tree | publisher = [[Tower Records]] | accessdate = 2009-12-02}}</ref> ''[[NME]]'' praised the album as "a better and braver record than anything else that's likely to appear in 1987. It's the sound of people confronting their own ghosts in a country where they can if they wish become a dusty speck on the landscape. It's the sound of people still trying, still looking (...)."<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Out of Little Acorns... | magazine = [[NME]] | first = John | last = McCready | date = 1987-03-14}}</ref>

In ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'}}s cover story on U2, the magazine called the album the band's best, commenting that it had both commercial and thematic depth.<ref name="bandonrun">{{cite web | url = http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,964182-1,00.html | title = U2: Band on the Run | publisher = ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' | first = Jay | last = Cocks | date = 1987-04-27 | accessdate = 2009-12-24}}</ref> Stephen Thomas Erlewine of [[Allmusic]] rated the album a perfect five-stars, saying, "their focus has never been clearer, nor has their music been catchier". Erlewine found it ironic the band achieved its greatest success with an album filled with such dark lyrical content. His review concluded, "Never before have U2's big messages sounded so direct and personal."<ref name="allmusic">{{cite web | url = http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=10:0jzsa9qgb23f | title = The Joshua Tree - Overview | publisher = [[Allmusic]] | first = Stephen Thomas | last = Erlewine | accessdate = 2009-12-02}}</ref> [[Sputnikmusic]] also gave the album a perfect five-star score.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sputnikmusic.com/album.php?reviewid=307 | title = U2 - The Joshua Tree Review | publisher = [[Sputnikmusic]] | first = Andrew | last = Hartwig | date = 2005-01-14 | accessdate = 2009-12-02}}</ref> [[Robert Hilburn]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' said the album "confirms on record what this band has been slowly asserting for three years now on stage: U2 is what the Rolling Stones ceased being years ago - the greatest rock and roll band in the world". Hilburn noted that the band expanded on the "sketches" from ''The Unforgettable Fire'' with "sometimes breathtaking signs of growth", playing more "tailored and assured" music.<ref>{{cite news | title = The Joshua Tree | newspaper = [[Los Angeles Times]] | first = Robert | last = Hilburn | authorlink = Robert Hilburn | date = 1987-03-15}}</ref> ''[[Hot Press]]'' editor and longtime U2 supporter Bill Graham said that "''The Joshua Tree'' rescues rock from its decay, bravely and unashamedly basing itself in the mainstream before very cleverly lifting off into several higher dimensions," and that U2 "must be taken very seriously indeed after this revaluation of rock".<ref>{{cite magazine | title = The Joshua Tree | magazine = [[Hot Press]] | first = Bill | last = Graham | date = 1987-03-12}}</ref>

[[Anthony DeCurtis]] of ''Rolling Stone'' summarized the album's examiniation of America both lyrically and musically as such:<ref>{{cite magazine | last =DeCurtis | first =Anthony| authorlink = Anthony DeCurtis | title =Truths and Consequences | magazine =[[Rolling Stone]] | date = 1987-05-07}}</ref>
{{blockquote|"The wild beauty, cultural richness, spiritual vacancy and ferocious violence of America are explored to compelling effect in virtually every aspect of ''The Joshua Tree''<U+2014>in the title and the cover art, the blues and country borrowings evident in the music&nbsp;... Indeed, Bono says that 'dismantling the mythology of America' is an important part of ''The Joshua Tree''{{'}}s artistic objective."}}

At the [[30th Grammy Awards]] in 1988, U2 won their first two [[Grammy Awards]], with the band receiving honors for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal|Best Rock Performance By a Duo or Group With Vocal]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.grammy.com/GRAMMY_Awards/Winners/Results.aspx?title=&winner=u2&year=1987&genreID=0&hp=1 | title = Grammy Award Winners - U2 in 1987 | work = [[Grammy Award|Grammy.com]] | publisher = [[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences|The Recording Academy]] | accessdate = 2010-04-23}}</ref>

==The Joshua Tree Tour==
{{Main|The Joshua Tree Tour}}
In support of the album, the band launched The Joshua Tree Tour. Consisting of three legs and a total of 111 shows, the tour took the band to arenas and stadiums worldwide from April 1987 to December 1987. Until the release of ''The Joshua Tree'', U2 had proportionally been more successful as a live act than as a record selling act.<ref name="classic-album" /> The album brought U2 to a new level of mega-stardom, as the tour sold out arenas and stadiums around the world, the first time the band had consistently played venues of that size. Performances of the third leg were recorded for the 1988 motion picture and companion album ''[[Rattle and Hum]]''.

==Legacy==
{{ Quote box 
| quote = "During the two decades that have elapsed since then, every move the band has made has been, in some way, a reaction to the legacy of ''The Joshua Tree''. ''[[Rattle and Hum]]'' was an extension of the album, further exploring American music forms such as blues, gospel, and soul. Then, inevitably, U2 got tired of living in their own shadow, and both ''[[Achtung Baby]]'' and ''[[Zooropa]]'' chipped away at expectations of the band. When they finally realized there was no escaping their iconic status sealed by ''The Joshua Tree'', U2 mocked it on ''[[Pop (album)|Pop]]''. By then, though, fans had grown weary of the band's experimentation, and U2 have spent their last two albums trying to recapture the radio-friendly sound of their 1987 opus."
| source = <U+2014>[[PopMatters]], in 2007<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/51169/u2-the-joshua-tree/ | title = U2: The Joshua Tree | publisher = [[PopMatters]] | first = Michael | last = Franco | date = 2007-11-26 | accessdate = 2010-04-26}}</ref>
| width = 30%
| align = right
| style = padding: 10px;
}}
''The Joshua Tree'' ranks as one of the [[List of best-selling albums in the United States|best-selling albums in the US]]. In 1995, the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]] awarded it a Diamond [[RIAA certification|certification]]<U+2014>the highest certification available<U+2014>indicating sales of 10&nbsp;million copies.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=tblDiamond | title = Gold & Platinum | work = [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]] | accessdate = 2010-04-28}}</ref><ref name="ussales">{{cite web |title=Top 100 Albums |work=[[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]] |url=http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=tblTop100 |accessdate=2009-11-25}}</ref> In the UK, the album is certified 6<U+00D7> Platinum, with an additional Silver certification for the 20th anniversary edition.<ref name="uksales" /> ''The Joshua Tree'' is the band's best-selling album, having sold 25&nbsp;million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.virginmedia.com/music/classicalbums/u2-thejoshuatree.php |title=The Joshua Tree|publisher=Virgin|accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref>

''The Joshua Tree'' is often cited as one of the greatest albums in rock history. In 1989, two years after its release, it was rated number three on ''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s list of "The 100 Greatest Albums of the 80's". In 2003, ''Rolling Stone'' ranked the album at number 26 on their list of "[[The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time]]";<ref>{{cite magazine | url = http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/;kw%3D%5B4175,12757,12870%5D | title=26.) The Joshua Tree |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=2003-11-01 | accessdate = 2010-04-20}}</ref> it was U2's best position on the list. "The Definitive 200" list, compiled by the [[National Association of Recording Merchandisers]] and sponsored by the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]], ranks the album as the fifth-greatest in history.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://web.archive.org/web/20080802040323/http://www.rockhall.com/pressroom/definitive-200/ |title=Definitive 200 |work=[[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] |author=[[National Association of Recording Merchandisers]] |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref> In 2006, the album appeared on a number of rankings, including ''[[Hot Press]]''{{'}}s "100 Greatest Albums Ever" at number 11,<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.hotpress.ie/archive/2860876.html |title=The Joshua Tree (11/100 Greatest Albums Ever) |magazine=[[Hot Press]] |date=2006-04-18}}</ref> and ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'}}s "The All-Time 100 Albums".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.time.com/time/2006/100albums/0,27693,Achtung_Baby,00.html |title=The All-Time 100 Albums: Achtung Baby |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |first=Josh |last=Tyrangiel |date=2006-11-13 |accessdate=2009-09-11}}</ref> That same year, ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' named it the best album of the 1980s,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/qlistspage3.htm#The Music That Changed The World | title = Q lists - The Music That Changed the World | publisher = Rock List Music | date = 2009-09-11}}</ref> while the publication's readers ranked it the 16th greatest album of all-time.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=The 100 Greatest Albums Ever! (as voted by you) |magazine=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |date=2006-02 |issue=235}}</ref> Music television channel [[VH1]] placed it at number 15 on their "100 Greatest Albums of Rock & Roll" program in ''[[The Greatest (TV series)|The Greatest]]'' series.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/cgi-bin/stories.pl?ACCT=104&STORY=/www/story/01-05-2001/0001397649 |title=VH1's '100 Greatest Albums of Rock & Roll' Ranks the Beatles' 'Revolver' at #1 In All-New Special, Premiering January 15<U+2013>19 at 10:00 P.M. (ET/PT) |work=[[PR Newswire]] |date=2001-01-05 |accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref> It has been listed as one of four U2 records in the 2006 music reference book ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]'' and its subsequent revised editions.<ref>{{cite book |title=[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]] |publisher=Universe Publishing |city=Hong Kong |isbn=0-7893-1371-5 |editor=Dimery, Robert |year=2006}}</ref> In 2008, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' ranked it at number 63 on its list of the greatest albums of the previous 25 years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20207076_20207387_20207337,00.html |title=EW 1000 - The New Classics: Music - The 100 best albums from 1983 to 2008 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref> In 2010, the album appeared at number 62 on ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''{{'}}s list of the "125 Best Albums of the Past 25 Years", which ranked the most influential albums in the 25 years since the magazine launched. The magazine wrote, "The band's fifth album spit out hits like crazy, and they were unusually searching hits, each with a pointed political edge."<ref>{{cite magazine | url = http://www.spin.com/spin25/125-best-albums-past-25-years#page=7 | title = 125 Best Albums of the Past 25 Years: 62 - U2, The Joshua Tree | magazine = [[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] | first1 = Andy | last1 = Battaglia | first2 = Scott | last2 = Indrisek | date = 2010-04-22 | accessdate = 2010-04-23}}</ref> Writing in 1996, Bill Graham said "the best young live band of their era had graduated as masterful pop mimics in the studio. With ''The Joshua Tree'', their recorded work finally [caught] up and even outstrip[ped] their live reputation."<ref>Graham (1996), p. 29, 33, 34</ref> 

The band's penchant for addressing political and social issues, as well as their staid depiction in Corbijn's black-and-white sleeve photographs contributed to the group's earnest and serious image as "stone-faced pilgrim[s]". This image became the target of derision after the band's critically-maligned motion picture and album ''[[Rattle and Hum]]'' were released in 1988.<ref name="westwon" /> Various critics called them "po-faced",<ref>{{cite magazine | title = The History of Pop | magazine = [[Hot Press]] | first = Niall | last = Stokes | authorlink = Niall Stokes | date = 1997-03-19}}</ref> "pompous bores",<ref name="chop-joshua">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.uncut.co.uk/music/u2/reviews/10793 |title=U2 - The Joshua Tree Re-Mastered (R1987) |magazine=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]] |first=Andrew |last=Mueller |accessdate=2009-12-31}}</ref> and "humourless".<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Confessions of a Rock Star | magazine = [[Hot Press]] | first = Neil | last = McCormick | date = 2000-12-15}}</ref> After telling fans they would "dream it all up again", U2 reinvented themselves in the 1990s with a sound inspired by [[alternative rock]] and [[electronic dance music]], and with a more self-deprecating, flippant image by which they embraced the "rock star" identity they struggled with in the 1980s.<ref name="ach-stations">{{cite magazine|title=Achtung Stations|magazine=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]|first=Stephen|last=Dalton|date=2004-10-26}}</ref> The band referred to their 1991 album ''[[Achtung Baby]]'' as "chopping down the Joshua Tree".<ref name="chop-joshua" /> Journalist Bill Flanagan summarised the impact of ''The Joshua Tree'' on the group's career in his liner notes to the album's 20th anniversary release: "''The Joshua Tree'' made U2 into international rock stars and established both a standard they would always have to live up to and an image they would forever try to live down."<ref name="box-liner">{{cite music release notes | Last = The Edge | Name = The Joshua Tree | Year = 2007 | Format = 20th anniversary edition box set | Artist = [[U2]]}}</ref>

==Track listing==
While the band and crew were working on the album's mixing, Lillywhite's wife, singer [[Kirsty MacColl]], volunteered to set the running order for the album. The band told her to put "Where the Streets Have No Name" first and "Mothers of the Disappeared" last. The rest were sequenced according to her preference, which the band kept.<ref name="McCormick 2006, p. 185"/>

